Variables: store information. You give it a name and put a value inside. Later, you can use that name to get the value back.

Creating your first variable
name = "Alice"
age = 25
is_student = True

Naming rules
Allowed:
user_name = "xyz"      # lowercase with underscores (Python style)
userName = "xyz"       # camelCase (works but not Python style)
age2 = 30              # numbers are OK (not at start)
_private = "secret"    # underscore at start is OK
Not allowed:
2age = 30              # Can't start with number
my-name = "xyz"       # No hyphens (Python thinks it's subtraction)
my name = "xyz"       # No spaces
class = "Python"       # Can't use Python keywords

Python naming convention
In Python, we use lowercase letters with underscores between words. This is called “snake_case” and it's the standard way to name variables in Python.

# Good Python style
first_name = "Alice"
user_age = 25
is_logged_in = True
shopping_cart_total = 49.99

Changing variables
Variables can change (that's why they're called variables!):
# Start with one value
score = 0
print(score)  # Shows: 0

# Change it
score = 10
print(score)  # Shows: 10

# Change it again
score = score + 5
print(score)  # Shows: 15
